BlazorCrud

Introduction
BlazorCrud is a web application developed with Blazor, showcasing CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations. The project seamlessly integrates Blazor components, SQL Server for data storage, and utilizes essential packages for user authentication and database management.

Project Overview
The project includes the following key functionalities:

Create: Add new records to the database.
Read: Retrieve and view details of existing records.
Update: Modify information and attributes of records.
Delete: Remove records from the database.
Technologies Used
The project leverages the following technologies and packages:

Blazor: A web framework for building interactive and client-side web applications.
Entity Framework Core: Object-relational mapping (ORM) for database interactions.
SQL Server: A database management system for data storage.
ASP.NET Core Identity: Provides a framework for user authentication and management.
Packages Used
The project utilizes the following essential packages:

Microsoft.AspNetCore.Identity.EntityFrameworkCore: Framework for user authentication and management.
Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer: Enables interaction with SQL Server databases.
Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Tools: Offers additional tools for Entity Framework Core development.
Features Covered
CRUD Operations: Implementation of Create, Read, Update, and Delete functionalities.
Blazor Components: Development of interactive and reusable UI components.
SQL Database Integration: Interaction with a SQL Server database for data storage.
User Authentication: Utilization of ASP.NET Core Identity for user authentication and management.
How to Use
Follow these steps to run the project locally:

Clone the repository.
Configure your SQL Server connection in the app settings.
Build and run the BlazorCrud application.
Explore the CRUD functionalities using the Blazor-based user interface.
Contribution Guidelines
Contributions are welcome! If you have enhancements, bug fixes, or new features to propose, follow these guidelines:

Create a new branch for your changes.
Make your modifications and ensure they align with existing coding conventions.
Submit a pull request with a clear description of the changes and their purpose.
